Introduction and Methods

This study will assess use of IRT with an examination. Three new NASCLA examination forms were constructed from items used for similar previous examinations. An IRT assessment paradigm, based on data from past administration of those items, is proposed. The items included in the new NASCLA forms were shown to perform equivalently (have equivalent difficulties) across different forms in which they were included in previously administered examinations (see previous report- Utah Contractors Exam) or were similar to those items and considered equivalent. As such, data from administration of those items obtained across forms can be pooled for item analysis for the IRT models (see Wright).

The approach for utilizing IRT with these items was to first extract individual response data for those items from previous examinations. Items were summarized. With those data, IRT models were constructed and evaluated. An algorithm for administering those items in hypothetical examinations was developed. Simulations were then conducted to compare the IRT model and adaptive algorithm with classical test methods and fixed selection of items.

Two broad approaches were useda variable-length approach were administration stopped when current ability level was 95% either above or below cut score and a fixed-number format, where a set number of items were administered. Both of these approaches were considered to accommodate different test distribution capabilities. Within both of these approaches, an adaptive IRT approach that sought items near the examinees ability level, a random IRT approach that randomly selected the same number of items as the adaptive approach, and a classical approach that used classical scoring methods with the same number of items were used:

  1. Variable Length
  1. IRT adaptive (determines number of items)
  2. IRT random (same number of items as adaptive)
  3. CTT (same number of items as adaptive)
  1. Fixed Length (all same set number of items)
  1. IRT item-level scoring
  2. IRT total-score scoring
  3. CTT total-score scoring

Simulations were conducted at varying assumed levels of underlying candidate latent ability. Estimated abilities and pass decisions were then compared for each of the above methods.

Models were assessed by:

  1. classification accuracy
  2. error
  3. closeness to target score
  4. number of items needed

This data analysis is generalized to allow for input of any vector of item titles and conduct the above procedures and then output results, as in this report, automatically. (Give specific selection criteria in following) In this particular report, the items are drawn from each of the three exams in turn. Data were queried with completion status complete, items marked correct as either Y or N (upon inspection found to be mostly redundant with completion status complete), and any date.

Minimum item counts and recent records

Rasch analysis generally requires at least 100 records of data per item, with higher parameter models needing more. In addition, item data was drawn from different forms from different administrations. Some IRT estimation tools can handle incomplete data, but severely incomplete data can cause estimation problems. A minimum of 200 administrations of an item for each exam that item was draw from was deemed necessary to include data for that item.

In addition, only data from 2017 or later were included, as that interval was examined in previous analysis. After filtering by these conditions, there were 337510 records. There were 157 different items from 53529 separate administrations to individual examinees total.

person_rows_item_columns_func <- function() {
  full_dat %>%
    dplyr::select(ITEM_TITLE, TEST_SESSION_ID, item_correct_numeric) %>%

    filter(rowSums(!is.na(.)) > 1) %>% 
    dplyr::select(where(~!all(is.na(.x))))
}

Rows (individuals) with only one level of response (0 or 1) were removed. This resulted in a dataset with 53529 records.

However, because data were gathered from multiple examinations and forms, there were a number of incomplete (NA) values in the data.

Model Construction

IRT modelling applications can have problems with a large number of NA values or for rows or columns with only one response level, which lead to rank deficiencies in model estimates. Multiple packages and models were considered for IRT modeling, with the MIRT package, using the Rasch (1PL) model, found to construct a suitable model.

However, it was not possible to obtain some typical model diagnostic information, such as model fit statistics, model standard error, or item-fit statistics due to the large percentage of incomplete cases. However, examining the item parameters and plots and overall measure of model reliability, suggested the model would be appropriate.

## Consider other IRT models, non converged except Rasch here

## Construct Rasch model from prepared data
rasch_mod <- mirt::mirt(
    person_rows_item_columns_func()[-1],
    1,
    itemtype = "Rasch",
    SE = TRUE,
    verbose = FALSE, # suppress iteration results
    accelerate = 'none'
)

# Parameter scores
nascla_difficulties <- function(){
  mirt::coef(rasch_mod, simplify = TRUE, IRTpars = TRUE)$items %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  tibble::rownames_to_column("question_content") %>% 
  dplyr::select(question_content, difficulty = b)
}
## Fit stats-not calculated here b/c incomplete data
# mirt::M2(rasch_mod, type = "C2", calcNULL = FALSE, na.rm = T)

# Information curve/ SE curve
mirt::plot(rasch_mod, type = 'infoSE', theta_lim = c(-3, 3), 
     main="Test Information/SE Curve")

# Test characteristic curve
plot(rasch_mod, type = 'score', theta_lim = c(-3, 3), main = "Test Characteristic Curve")

# Plot of reliability across theta- conditional reliability
mirt::plot(rasch_mod, type = 'rxx', theta_lim = c(-3, 3), 
     main="Conditional Reliability")

# Item loadings onto factor
capture.output(summary(rasch_mod)) -> out

The model converged with a marginal reliability of 0.96 and SS Loadings of 24.45. The mean difficulty score was -0.97.

(Interpret) It seems that the model provides maximum information at around ability levels of -1. The model has peak information at that theta value. Items average around that value. It is not surprising as average p-values for all items were 0.68. That is about one standard deviation easier than the mean, similarly represented in the logit scale. For these reasons, -1 will be used as a cut score for simulations below.

Adaptive Asssessment

An algorithm was devised to efficiently administer items to a hypothetical candidate to determine the candidates ability and if the candidate would meet a given cut score (-1). The algorithm also prioritized presenting a diverse array of items to avoid duplicating items.

The algorithm was then tested in hypothetical scenarios to evaluate performance. Candidates were assigned underlying latent abilities (ground truth) and the accuracy of the model in correctly classifying pass decision was calculated and compared with IRT methods with random selection and CTT methods. The simulated scenarios were run multiple times and performance statistics gathered.

Algorithm Description

Heres a general description of the algorithm and simulation methodsfrom the item-bank, a range of items generally within the candidates estimated ability level are identified. One item is randomly selected (to increase variety of items administered). The candidates response to the item is generated, based on the underlying latent ability and item difficulty. The candidates estimated ability level is then updated based on that and previous item responses and the procedure is repeated. Of note, as the standard error becomes less, the range of candidate items becomes smaller and more preceise. In the variable-length simulation conditions, this is repeated until the candidates estimated ability level is outside the cut-score ability level, withini 95% CI. In the fixed-length conditions, the procedure is repeated for a specified number of items.

###*** These are user selected values based on desired exam and candidate characteristics to be hand-adjusted
items_per_exam <- 50 # maximum number of items presented
current_candidate_latent_ability <- .5 # Only for coding; is iterated through in simulations below
pass_score <- -1
# Df of difficulties paired with items
irt_model_coefficients <- nascla_difficulties()

###*** Test characteristics of logistic scale
absolute_sd <- 1
absolute_max_score <- max(irt_model_coefficients$difficulty)
absolute_min_score <- min(irt_model_coefficients$difficulty)

###*** Generate 0 or 1 response based on logistic function and candidate ability
###* This will be used for each selected item to generate a response
is_response_correct_func <- function(item_difficulty, current_candidate_latent_ability){
  # rbinom chooses 0 or 1 for given probability
  rbinom(n = 1, size = 1, prob = 
           # logistic function solved for P
  exp(1.7*(current_candidate_latent_ability - item_difficulty)) / 
    (1 + exp(1.7*(current_candidate_latent_ability - item_difficulty)))
  )
}

###*** Initialize global variables that are used to track data over administration of items
initialize_variables_func <- function(){

# Dataset to track correct and incorrect responses
response_dat <<- tibble()
response_vector <<- tibble()

# This dataset will hold remaining candidate items. As each item is administered it is removed, so as not to duplicate items
filtered_dat <<- irt_model_coefficients 

# These hold candidate ability scores and are updated with each response as factor score fed with candidate response vector
  # initialize with this as we want items near pass score and can't know candidate information beforehand
current_score <<- pass_score 
current_se <<- absolute_sd

###*** This prepares the first item and removes it from filtered_dat
filtered_dat %>% 
  # Get item pool within +/- standard error of candidate current ability
  filter(between(difficulty, 
                 current_score - current_se, 
                 current_score + current_se)) %>%
  {. -> tmp
    # This step ensures there are items within that range. If not selects closest
    if(nrow(tmp) == 0){
      # Gets closest item
      tmp <- filtered_dat %>%
        slice_min(abs(current_score - difficulty))
    } else{
      # Randomly select item within se range
      tmp <- slice_sample(tmp, n = 1)
    }
    # Hold selected item as current item
    current_item <<- tmp
    # Remove that item from item pool
    filtered_dat <<- filtered_dat %>% 
      anti_join(., tmp, by = "question_content")
  }
}

###*** This function gathers administered items, candidate responses, candidate ability estimates, and prepares next question based on current ability
select_next_question_func<- function(points_to_add){

# Holds all responses, will add 0 or 1 based on correct or incorrect response, determined when this function is applied  
response_dat <<- bind_rows(response_dat, # add new item as row
                           current_item %>%
                             dplyr::select(-difficulty) %>% 
                             mutate(points = points_to_add)
                           )

###*** Join all responses with data that holds irt parameters. Will order responses in same order as rasch coefficients to input response vector
response_vector <<- left_join(irt_model_coefficients, 
                             response_dat, 
                             by = "question_content"
                             )

# Get current score and se at each administration of items
current_score <<- mirt::fscores(rasch_mod, 
                                response.pattern = response_vector$points)[1]

current_se <<- mirt::fscores(rasch_mod, 
                             response.pattern = response_vector$points)[2]

###*** filtered_dat is unused item pool. From it new item is chosen based on candidate current ability, within range of se. Items randomly selected within that interval for administration variety  
filtered_dat %>% 
  # Get item pool within +/- standard error of candidate current ability
  filter(between(difficulty, 
                 current_score - current_se, 
                 current_score + current_se)) %>%
  {. -> tmp
    # This step ensures there are items within that range. If not selects closest
    if(nrow(tmp) == 0){
      # Gets closest item
      tmp <- filtered_dat %>%
        slice_min(abs(current_score - difficulty))
    } else{
      # Randomly select item within se range
      tmp <- slice_sample(tmp, n = 1)
    }
    # Hold selected item as current item
    current_item <<- tmp
    # Remove that item from item pool
    filtered_dat <<- filtered_dat %>% 
      anti_join(., tmp, by = "question_content")
  }
}

###*** Function first checks to see if candidate within standard error of pass_score. If outside that range, a decision can be made about passing and no more items administered. If within range, administers current item, determines if correct response, based on candidate ability and item difficulty, then prepares next item 
item_selector_func <- function(current_candidate_latent_ability){
  # If current store within standard error of cut score, administer more questions, else stop
  if(between(pass_score, 
             current_score - 1.96*current_se, 
             current_score + 1.96*current_se)
     ){
    # Determine if a correct response, then add item with point (1) or (0)
    select_next_question_func(is_response_correct_func(current_item$difficulty, current_candidate_latent_ability))
  }
}
###*** Apply above functions to "administer test"
# Administer across different underlying ability conditions
purrr::map(
  .x = seq(-2, 1, .5), # Different latent abilities
  .f = function(current_candidate_latent_ability){ # list for each ability
purrr::map_dfr(1:50,~{ # Times to administer each exam
    # Reset all holder variables
    initialize_variables_func()
    # Administer each exam. items_per_exam is max number of items per exam
    replicate(items_per_exam, item_selector_func(current_candidate_latent_ability) -> tmp) # tmp suppresses output
    # Get summary of each exam
    as.data.frame(tibble(
      # Z-score of number correct
      number_items_administered = nrow(response_dat),
      # Given items candidate responded to, how many should be correct?
      expected_items_correct = expected.test(rasch_mod, 
                                             Theta = 
                                          matrix(current_candidate_latent_ability),
                                             which.items =
                                            which(!is.na(response_vector$points))),
      # Number of items correct
      actual_items_correct = sum(response_dat$points, na.rm = TRUE),
      # Current candidate ability score
      candidate_ability_estimate = current_score,
      # Current standard error
      ability_estimate_se = current_se,
      # z score of number correct/number administered
      z_score_ctt = (sum(response_dat$points)/nrow(response_dat)) %>%
               qnorm(, mean = 0, sd = 1)
    )) %>% 
      # Taking a random sample of the same number of items administered in adaptive testing, what is the irt ability score and se?
    bind_cols(.,
              # Calculate probability of success and evaluate success based on this
              response_vector %>%
                rowwise() %>%
                mutate(
                  # Probability of success
                  person_item_probability =
                    exp(1.7*(current_candidate_latent_ability - difficulty)) /
               (1 + exp(1.7*(current_candidate_latent_ability - difficulty))),
                  # Random success or not
                  expected_response = is_response_correct_func(difficulty,
                                                current_candidate_latent_ability)
               ) %>%
    ungroup %>%
      # From those calculated successes, take a sample of the same size as items administered, replace rest with NA
    mutate(expected_response =  replace(expected_response, 
                                    # Sample row numbers of unadminstered item size
                                        sample(row_number(),
                                               size = (
                                                 nrow(response_vector) -
                                                   nrow(response_dat)
                                                 ), 
                                               replace = FALSE), NA) 
           ) %$% 
      # Get factor score from this sampled vector
    fscores(rasch_mod, response.pattern = .$expected_response) %>%
      as.data.frame() %>% 
      rename("fixed_items_ability" = "F1", 
             "fixed_items_SE" = "SE_F1")
    ) %>% # End bind_cols
      mutate(
        items_administered = list(tibble(items = response_dat$question_content))
        )
    })  %>% # End map- the administration of all forms
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), round, 2)) %>% 
  rowwise() %>% 
  mutate(
    z_score_ctt = case_when(
      identical(z_score_ctt, Inf) ~ 3,
      identical(z_score_ctt, -Inf) ~ -3,
      TRUE ~ z_score_ctt),
    decision = case_when(
      candidate_ability_estimate < pass_score & current_candidate_latent_ability < pass_score ~ "true_fail",
      candidate_ability_estimate > pass_score & current_candidate_latent_ability > pass_score ~ "true_pass",
      candidate_ability_estimate < pass_score & current_candidate_latent_ability > pass_score ~ "false_fail",
      candidate_ability_estimate > pass_score & current_candidate_latent_ability < pass_score ~ "false_pass",
      TRUE ~ "inconclusive"
    ), .before = 1
  ) %>% 
  ungroup
}) %>% 
  purrr::set_names(seq(-2, 1, .5)) -> sim_dat

Simulation Results

Simulations were conducted with the algorithm and models. First the adpative algorithm was run 50 times each for assumed underlying candidate latent ability levels of -2 to 1 by .5. The algorithm stopped when a 95% CI decision could be made about pass/fail. The adaptive condition, along with IRT and CTT random selection of (the same number) of administered items, and resulting outcomes were considered.

Fixed Length

A set number of items (75) were administered. Candidate abilities were estimated using response vector with weighted item points, IRT total scores, and CTT percentages, transformed to standard scores. Underlying latent abilities from -1.5 to -.5 (by .1) were used, to focus on marginal candidates. In the

fixed_sim_dat <- purrr::map_dfr(
  .x = seq(-1.5, -.5, .1), # Underlying ability estimates
  .f = ~{
  current_candidate_latent_ability <- .x
  # Administer adaptive model
  purrr::map_dfr(1:50,~{ # Times to administer each exam
    # Reset all holder variables
    initialize_variables_func()
    # Administer each exam. items_per_exam is max number of items per exam
    items_per_exam = 75
    replicate(items_per_exam, 
              select_next_question_func(
      is_response_correct_func(current_item$difficulty,
                        current_candidate_latent_ability)) -> tmp)

    ## Df of all items and difficulties and probabilities of correct, with assumed response, to be sampled for total score and ctt    
total_correct_sample <- response_vector %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(
    # Probability of success
    person_item_probability =
      exp(1.7*(current_candidate_latent_ability - difficulty)) /
      (1 + exp(1.7*(current_candidate_latent_ability - difficulty))),
    # Random success or not
    expected_response = is_response_correct_func(
      difficulty,
      current_candidate_latent_ability)

    ungroup %>%
      # From those calculated successes, take a sample of the same size as items administered, replace rest with NA
    mutate(

        # Sample row numbers of unadminstered item size
        sample(row_number(),
               size = (nrow(response_vector) - nrow(response_dat)),
               replace = FALSE), NA) 
           )
# Total correct from random selection of items
sum_correct_fixed <- total_correct_sample %>% 
  summarise(total_correct = sum(expected_response, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  dplyr::select(total_correct) %>% pull

# Total scores and accompanying thetas for items selected
fixed_exam_theta <- tibble(
      theta = seq(-3,3,.1), 
      score = expected.test(
        rasch_mod, 
        Theta = matrix(seq(-3,3,.1)),
        which.items = which(!is.na(total_correct_sample$expected_response))
      )
    ) %>% 
  rowwise() %>% 
  # Subtract each score from the candidate score
  mutate(
    score_difference = abs(score - sum_correct_fixed)
  ) %>% 
  ungroup %>% 
  # Fine closest score and get accompanying theta
  slice_min(score_difference) %>% 
  dplyr::select(theta) %>% pull
    
    tibble(
      adaptive_exam_theta = mirt::fscores(rasch_mod, 
                      response.pattern = response_vector$points)[1],
      adaptive_exam_se = mirt::fscores(rasch_mod, 
                    response.pattern = response_vector$points)[2],
      fixed_exam_theta,
      latent_ability = current_candidate_latent_ability,
      z_score_ctt = (sum_correct_fixed/items_per_exam) %>% 
        qnorm(, mean = 0, sd = 1)
    )
}) %>% 
    # Correct for when all items answered correctly or incorrectly, assign extreme z
    mutate(
      z_score_ctt = case_when(
      identical(z_score_ctt, Inf) ~ 3,
      identical(z_score_ctt, -Inf) ~ -3,
      TRUE ~ z_score_ctt),
      latent_ability = .x) %>% 
    rowwise() %>% 
    # Get decision accuracies
    mutate(
      adaptive_decision = case_when(
      adaptive_exam_theta + 1.96*adaptive_exam_se < pass_score & .x < pass_score ~ "true_fail",
      adaptive_exam_theta - 1.96*adaptive_exam_se > pass_score & .x > pass_score ~ "true_pass",
      adaptive_exam_theta + 1.96*adaptive_exam_se < pass_score & .x > pass_score ~ "false_fail",
      adaptive_exam_theta - 1.96*adaptive_exam_se > pass_score & .x < pass_score ~ "false_pass",
      TRUE ~ "inconclusive"
      ),
      fixed_decision = case_when(
      fixed_exam_theta + 1.96*adaptive_exam_se < pass_score & .x < pass_score ~ "true_fail",
      fixed_exam_theta - 1.96*adaptive_exam_se > pass_score & .x > pass_score ~ "true_pass",
      fixed_exam_theta + 1.96*adaptive_exam_se < pass_score & .x > pass_score ~ "false_fail",
      fixed_exam_theta - 1.96*adaptive_exam_se > pass_score & .x < pass_score ~ "false_pass",
      TRUE ~ "inconclusive"
      ),
      ctt_decision = case_when(
      z_score_ctt + 1.96*adaptive_exam_se < pass_score & .x < pass_score ~ "true_fail",
      z_score_ctt  - 1.96*adaptive_exam_se > pass_score & .x > pass_score ~ "true_pass",
      z_score_ctt  + 1.96*adaptive_exam_se < pass_score & .x > pass_score ~ "false_fail",
      z_score_ctt  - 1.96*adaptive_exam_se > pass_score & .x < pass_score ~ "false_pass",
      TRUE ~ "inconclusive"
      )
    ) %>% 
    ungroup
  })

Discussion

This analysis demonstrated how to use IRT model estimation with a given group of items. As noted, data were not ideal for IRT analysis, due to NA values across administration. Data were cleaned to make more appropriate. A Rasch model was found useful for estimating item difficulties and had meaningful and solid metrics for use in a credentialing scenario. An algorithm for adaptive administration of the model was constructed.

Simulations were run to evaluate the model and algorithm under different conditions. The adaptive IRT model was efficient. It used the minimal number of items necessary to confidently assess candidate pass/fail decisions. It was extremely accurate in those decisions with respect to what should be expected given assumed underlying abilities. An IRT model that randomly selected the same number of items was less efficient when using the same number of items as the adaptive method. It would have benefitted from additional item assessment. Nonetheless, it would be useful and was closely accurate to the adaptive method. The CTT method was less accurate.

A fixed-length form was assumed. Scoring the model by items with IRT, scoring with total scores with IRT, and total scores with CTT were evaluated. The item-level model was more accurate across latent abilities. The total score method was slightly less accurate but was comparably accurate at cut-score ability levels. The CTT method gave inflated scores.

Taken together, an IRT adaptive paradigm would be the most accurate and valid method. IRT methods that scored by random selection, but used item-level data would also be beneficial but would require some additional items. The drawbacks to using these methods would be that the system would require IRT score conversion methods, which may be impractical. To address that IRT methods using a fixed-length form were considered. IRT methods that scored by items were superior. IRT methods that scored by total scores were very close. These methods could be more easily implemented in a system without IRT estimation and scoring capabilities. A number of forms with set items and scores based on those responses could be constructed. Using total scores for those set items could be easily implemented for paper or computer administration.
